Well, I’m far from fluent in Hawaiian, and don’t know much Maori, but there were words that looked similar. They’re considered to be “sibling languages”, if that makes sense. I saw the word Au used, which in Hawaiian can mean I or I am. Such as, maikaʻi au, I am good. A big thing that separates the languages is that Maori has more letters than Hawaiian does, as we have no T, R, Wh Ng sounds.
What a dick! As a linguist, I love hearing other people talk. Although I can’t speak Māori, I am a Hawaiian student, and there are many similarities. They are beautiful languages!
